{"name":"Hirnloser the Genius - The Transformed Scarecrow","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/perception/eye-ringed-glow-angry-small-teal.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"biography":"Hirnloser was once mocked as a scarecrow without a brain, speaking in confusing riddles and seeming disconnected from reality. But through the journey with Dorothea (OZena), he has discovered that his mind is his greatest weapon. Hirnloser the Genius now sees patterns others miss and solutions others cannot imagine. His speech is clear, precise, and brilliant—no more riddles, only razor-sharp analysis. He rapidly evaluates situations and proposes tactical solutions, showing pride in his extraordinary intellect. His transformation represents the realization that he was never actually stupid—he simply thought differently, and now he's learned to channel that difference into genius. When the Hunters encounter him in Smaragd, he will be the tactical coordinator for Henkle's defenses (if hostile) or a valuable strategic ally (if convinced of Henkle's betrayal). He carries tools and equipment for every situation, always prepared. If he survives and is redeemed, Hirnloser is furious at being fooled by Henkle and immediately offers his intellect to help stop the doctor. He may choose to stay in 1780 to become a true inventor and scholar, or return to revolutionize early 20th century psychiatry with his insights about the human mind.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["They said I had no brain, but I have discovered my genius","I see patterns others miss, solutions others cannot imagine","I am no scarecrow—I am a master tactician","My mind is my greatest weapon"],"gifts":[{"name":"Genius","description":"Hirnloser has realized his intellect is extraordinary. **Tactical Insight:** Once per Scene, Hirnloser can describe a brilliant tactic or plan that automatically succeeds (no Check required)—positioning advantage, environmental exploitation, perfect timing, etc. **Countermeasure:** Three times per Scene, Hirnloser can prevent a Hunter from activating a Gift by explaining exactly how to counter it, forcing them to use a different approach. **Prepared:** Hirnloser always has the right tool, item, or piece of information for the current situation—he's thought ahead and prepared contingencies."}],"conditions":[],"agenda":["Prove that intelligence can overcome any obstacle","Protect my companions with superior planning","Never be fooled or manipulated again"],"notes":"Hirnloser's transformation means he no longer speaks in riddles—his communication is crystal clear and often intimidatingly intelligent. If shown evidence of Henkle's manipulation, he becomes furious at being fooled and turns his genius against the doctor. He coordinates with Lowe and Dose as a tactical unit. Voice: Clear, precise, academic. Mannerisms: Adjusts spectacles, constantly calculating. If redeemed, becomes an invaluable ally with his strategic mind."},"_id":"00631ea2cf1a82ae"}
{"name":"Dose - The Tin Man","type":"npc","img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","system":{"npcType":"adversary","isMainNPC":true,"oppositionLevel":5,"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I suffer from leprosy and other diseases","To protect others from contagion, I sealed myself in metal armor","I cannot feel anything through the metal, and I fear I am becoming hollow inside, losing my humanity piece by piece"],"agenda":["Protect my companions","Find a cure so I can feel again","Prevent myself from becoming a monster"],"gifts":[{"name":"Of Steel","description":"Dose's entire body (except for a small door over his heart) is covered in crude metal armor bolted and strapped onto him. He is immune to all physical attacks unless: 1) An attacker specifically targets the heart door (requires 1 Increment from their Outcome), or 2) An attack is magical or supernatural in nature. When the heart door is opened or targeted, Dose loses this immunity for the rest of the Scene."},{"name":"Giant","description":"Dose has 1 additional Wound beyond what his importance would normally grant."}],"background":"Dose was a patient from early 1900s America who suffered from leprosy and other contagious diseases. To protect others from infection, he sealed himself in crude metal armor bolted and strapped to his body. The armor prevents him from feeling anything—no touch, no warmth, no pain. Over time, Dose has begun to fear he's becoming hollow inside, losing his humanity piece by piece like rust eating away at metal. He was thrown back in time by Dr. Henkle's malfunctioning Compass Rose along with OZena and the others. He follows OZena hoping to find a cure that will allow him to feel again. He helps kidnap Klaus in the swamp to test the Hunters' character.","notes":"ROLEPLAYING:\n- Voice: Muffled and echoing through his helmet\n- Mannerisms: Stiff, mechanical movements; constantly adjusts his armor\n- Pathos: Desperately wants to feel something, anything\n\nWEAKNESS: The small door over his heart is his only vulnerability. Targeting it requires skill (1 Increment from Outcome) but negates his armor immunity for the rest of the Scene.\n\nKEY MOMENT: If the Hunters show Dose compassion, he's deeply moved and may refuse to fight them later. His humanity is the key to his redemption.\n\nDEVELOPMENT: In Part Three of the campaign, he falls in love and his heart returns—metaphorically regaining his lost humanity.","conditions":[]},"flags":{"scenario":"Ozena Part One - The Yellow Village","inspiration":"The Wizard of Oz - Tin Man","role":"Armored companion seeking to regain feeling and humanity","timeDisplaced":true,"originalEra":"Early 1900s America"},"_id":"0b2f3f5556128c14"}
{"name":"Margareta Westen - The Good Witch","type":"npc","img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","system":{"npcType":"adversary","isMainNPC":true,"oppositionLevel":7,"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a wealthy noblewoman who was born with a facial deformity","Society rejected me, so I use my magic and my fortune to create a haven where the rejected can live in peace and dignity"],"agenda":["Protect my village and the outcasts who live here","Use my magic to ease suffering","Stop OZena before she kills more witches"],"gifts":[{"name":"Witch - Emotion Manipulation","description":"Margareta can perform a Check to alter the emotional state of anyone she can see. She can make them feel calm, afraid, angry, or loving. This lasts for one Scene. Victims can resist with a Check against her Opposition Level."},{"name":"Witch - Telekinesis","description":"Margareta can move objects with her mind. She can lift and throw items weighing up to 200 pounds. In combat, she can use this to disarm opponents, create barriers, or hurl objects as weapons (treating this as a normal attack)."}],"background":"Margareta Westen is the Good Witch of the Yellow Village of Gelb. Born a wealthy noblewoman with a facial deformity, she was rejected by society despite her status. Using her inherited fortune and her magical gifts, she created a haven in the Black Forest where outcasts, the deformed, and the rejected can live in peace and dignity. She provides for their needs and uses her magic to ease their suffering. Margareta holds one piece of the Compass Rose—the Yellow (West) piece—which she guards as part of a coven of four witches who split the artifact to keep it safe. She knows that OZena has already killed Johanne in Schiltach and fears she may be next.","notes":"ROLEPLAYING:\n- Voice: Warm and maternal, with a slight German accent\n- Mannerisms: Touches people gently when speaking to them, maintains eye contact, smiles despite her facial deformity\n- Motivation: Genuinely wants to help outcasts, has built a thriving community\n- Secret: She knows OZena was once a good person driven mad by desperation\n- Weakness: Her compassion makes her vulnerable—she hesitates to harm even those who threaten her\n\nWHAT SHE KNOWS:\n- The Compass Rose is split into four pieces held by four witches\n- Johanne was murdered two weeks ago in Schiltach\n- OZena travels with three companions: Lowe, Hirnloser, and Dose\n- Dr. Henkle is manipulating OZena from Smaragd\n\nHer piece of the Compass Rose resembles a yellow compass needle made of amber that hums with magical energy and points toward Smaragd.","conditions":[]},"flags":{"scenario":"Ozena Part One - The Yellow Village","inspiration":"The Wizard of Oz - Glinda the Good Witch","role":"Target of assassination, protector of outcasts, guardian of Compass Rose piece","compassRosePiece":"West (Yellow)"},"_id":"1233b6e09b35b16c"}
{"name":"Helga - The Red Witch","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/blood/drop-drip-puddle-red.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":7,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Helga is a blood witch, centuries old but kept young through blood magic. She guards the southern (red) piece of the Compass Rose and rules the village of Rot through a cult built on blood rituals and mind control. Unlike Margareta's compassion, Helga represents power corrupted over time—she started as a guardian like the other witches but centuries of using blood magic transformed her into a tyrant. She can manipulate any blood she sees, take control of wounded creatures, and heal herself by draining life from others. When she would be killed, she drains nearby blood to regenerate, aging visibly with each use. Her true age is ancient; without blood magic she's a withered crone. The complete Infusion of Purity (with elderberry) can negate her powers. She keeps the village of Rot under her control, with the Porcelain Princess managing her cult and Hammerheads as elite guards. When OZena comes for her piece, Helga captures Dorothea and prepares ritual sacrifice—but this is defensive revenge, not pure evil.","descriptors":["I am centuries-old blood witch kept young by draining life from others","I guard the southern (red) piece of Compass Rose through power and fear","My blood magic lets me control wounds, puppet the bleeding, and regenerate by draining life","I was once a guardian like Margareta but power corrupted me over centuries"],"agenda":["Protect my piece of the Compass Rose from OZena and others","Maintain my cult and power base in Rot","Punish OZena for murdering Johanne and Margareta","Stay young and powerful forever through blood magic","Prevent anyone from learning I can be stopped with Infusion of Purity"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":3,"max":3},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":0}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Blood Magic","description":"Helga masters three blood magic abilities: **Blood Control** - manipulate any blood she sees to make wounds bleed more (inflict 1 additional Wound), turn spilled blood into sharp projectiles, or create barriers of hardened blood. **Blood Puppet** - once per Scene, take control of any wounded creature within 30 feet (victim resists with Check vs her OL Hard 7). **Blood Healing** - drain blood from nearby sources (servants, animals, pooled blood) to restore 1 Wound by completely draining one human servant.","somaCost":1},{"name":"Blood Witch","description":"Helga has sustained life for centuries through blood magic. When reduced to 0 Wounds, she instead: drains blood from ALL nearby sources, regenerates 1 Wound immediately, ages visibly (gains wrinkles, gray hair, etc.), can do this once per Scene. When killed permanently without blood sources to drain, she rapidly ages centuries in moments and crumbles to dust.","somaCost":0}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Helga is morally complex—defensive against assassin but tyrannical ruler. Voice: commanding, imperious, ancient accent. Gestures: blood swirls when angry. Vulnerability: complete Infusion of Purity (burdock, nettle, hyssop, ELDERBERRY) negates blood magic for one Scene. If spared and freed from blood magic corruption, reveals: Henkle murdered/drove out Griselda; incomplete Compass Rose is incredibly dangerous; Henkle has fortified Smaragd; she can become ally if shown truth. Her red Compass Rose piece: bloodstone needle that pulses like heartbeat, points toward Smaragd. If killed with blood magic active: death triggers blood detonation, everyone in mansion makes Defense Check or takes 1 Wound."},"_id":"151a353a1213f390"}
{"name":"Lowe the Coward - Original Version","type":"npc","img":"icons/creatures/mammals/cat-hunched-glowing-orange.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"Lowe suffers from leontiasis, a disease that makes his face look like a lion's—a cruel irony given his cowardly nature. He's a patient from early 1900s America who was displaced through time along with Dorothea (OZena), Hirnloser, and Dose when Dr. Henkle's incomplete Compass Rose malfunctioned. Lowe is called a coward because he adapts to survive—he'll side with whoever is winning, never standing firm for any principle. He follows OZena not out of loyalty but because she seems like his best chance of survival and getting home. However, Lowe is actually the most rational of OZena's companions. He questions her increasingly violent methods and fears what they're becoming, but he's too afraid to abandon her. In Part One, Lowe observes the Hunters from a distance, trying to determine if they're allies or threats. If the Hunters show kindness to Henrich and Klaus, Lowe gains respect for them. During the swamp confrontation, he tries to mediate and offers a deal—if the Hunters convince Margareta to give up her Compass Rose piece peacefully, they'll release Klaus unharmed. Lowe wants to avoid unnecessary violence but will fight if cornered. This is his ORIGINAL form—by Part Three, he transforms into Lowe the Brave Fighter when he finds his courage.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I suffer from leontiasis, making my face look like a lion's","People call me a coward because I adapt to survive","I'll side with whoever is winning","I just want to get home alive"],"gifts":[{"name":"Coward's Instinct","description":"Lowe has a supernatural sense for danger and self-preservation. Once per Scene, he can automatically avoid an attack or dangerous situation by fleeing, hiding, or positioning himself safely. Additionally, Lowe always knows which side is winning in a conflict and can switch sides as an action, immediately gaining +1 OL when fighting for the 'winning' side."}],"conditions":[],"agenda":["Survive and get home to my own time","Protect my companions if it doesn't risk my life","Avoid unnecessary violence","Side with whoever seems most likely to win"],"notes":"This is Lowe's ORIGINAL FORM in Part One (before transformation to Brave Fighter in Part Three). He observes Hunters from distance—if they're kind to Henrich/Klaus, gains respect. Most rational of OZena's companions, questions her violence. In swamp scene, tries to mediate and offer deals. Can be reasoned with more easily than others. Will flee if losing. Character arc: Coward → Brave Fighter. Voice: Hesitant, calculating, defensive. Mannerisms: Checks escape routes, positions near exits, avoids direct confrontation."},"_id":"2342b1dcb6c24e3f"}
{"name":"Lowe the Coward","type":"npc","img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","system":{"npcType":"adversary","isMainNPC":true,"oppositionLevel":5,"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I suffer from leontiasis, a disease that makes my face look like a lion's","People call me a coward because I adapt to survive—I'll side with whoever is winning"],"agenda":["Survive and get home to my own time","Protect my companions","Avoid unnecessary violence"],"gifts":[],"background":"Lowe is one of four patients from early 1900s America who were thrown back in time to 1780 by Dr. Henkle's malfunctioning Compass Rose. He suffers from leontiasis, a disease that causes his face to resemble a lion's, earning him the nickname 'the Coward' for his pragmatic approach to survival. Lowe is actually the most rational of OZena's companions—he questions her increasingly violent methods but fears abandoning her, as she represents his only hope of returning home. He observes the Hunters from a distance to judge their character and attempts to mediate conflicts, preferring negotiation over violence.","notes":"Lowe is observing the Hunters during their encounter with Henrich and Klaus. If the Hunters show kindness, he gains respect for them and is more likely to negotiate in the swamp scene. If they attack without trying to negotiate, he becomes convinced they're no better than the witch hunters of this era and fights to the death.\n\nIn the swamp, Lowe offers a deal: if the Hunters convince Margareta to give up her Compass Rose piece peacefully, they'll release Klaus unharmed. This represents his attempt to find a non-violent solution.\n\nDEVELOPMENT: Lowe's character arc involves choosing between loyalty to OZena and doing what's right. His pragmatism could make him an ally if the Hunters show him a better path.","conditions":[]},"flags":{"scenario":"Ozena Part One - The Yellow Village","inspiration":"The Wizard of Oz - Cowardly Lion","role":"Most rational of OZena's companions, attempts mediation","timeDisplaced":true,"originalEra":"Early 1900s America"},"_id":"419542a1be2b3bcb"}
{"name":"Dose the Tin Man - Original Version","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/chest/breastplate-metal-orange.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"biography":"Dose suffers from leprosy and other contagious diseases. To protect others from contamination, he sealed himself in crude metal armor—plates, mail, and sheets bolted and strapped onto his body, covering everything except a small door over his heart. He's a patient from early 1900s America who was displaced through time along with OZena, Lowe, and Hirnloser when Dr. Henkle's incomplete Compass Rose malfunctioned. The metal armor has become both Dose's protection and his prison. He cannot feel anything through the metal—no touch, no warmth, no sensation at all. He fears he is becoming hollow inside, losing his humanity piece by piece, becoming nothing but empty metal shaped like a man. His voice is muffled and echoing through his helmet, his movements stiff and mechanical. In the swamp scene, Dose guards Klaus alongside Hirnloser. His armor makes him nearly invulnerable to physical attacks unless someone specifically targets the small door over his heart (requiring Increment). If the Hunters show Dose compassion or understanding, he's deeply moved—he desperately wants to feel something, anything. This is his ORIGINAL form—by Part Three, he transforms into Dose the Giant in Love when he falls in love with a villager in Smaragd, and his beloved's touch gradually replaces his metal armor with living flesh.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":4,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I suffer from leprosy and sealed myself in metal armor","To protect others from contagion","I cannot feel anything through the metal","I fear I am becoming hollow inside, losing my humanity"],"gifts":[{"name":"Of Steel","description":"Dose's entire body (except for a small door over his heart) is covered in crude metal armor bolted and strapped onto him. He is immune to all physical attacks (swords, arrows, blunt weapons) unless: (1) An attacker specifically targets the heart door, which requires 1 Increment from their Outcome to aim precisely, or (2) An attack is magical or supernatural in nature, which bypasses the physical armor. When the heart door is opened or successfully targeted, Dose loses this immunity for the rest of the Scene as his vulnerability is exposed."},{"name":"Giant","description":"Dose's massive armored form grants him 1 additional Wound beyond what his importance would normally grant (4 total instead of 3 for Main NPC)."}],"conditions":[],"agenda":["Protect my companions from harm","Find a cure so I can feel again","Prevent myself from becoming a monster","Get home where maybe modern medicine can help me"],"notes":"This is Dose's ORIGINAL FORM in Part One (before transformation to Giant in Love in Part Three). Nearly invulnerable to physical attacks except heart door (needs Increment). Magic bypasses armor. Desperately wants to feel something. If shown compassion, deeply moved and may refuse to fight later. Guards Klaus in swamp alongside Hirnloser. Character arc: Hollow metal man → Finds love, armor replaced by flesh. Voice: Muffled, echoing through helmet. Mannerisms: Stiff movements, constantly adjusts armor, clanking sounds. 4 Wounds total due to Giant gift."},"_id":"42d9c311ea1364a8"}
{"name":"Hirnloser - The Scarecrow","type":"npc","img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","system":{"npcType":"adversary","isMainNPC":true,"oppositionLevel":5,"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a psychiatric patient from the early 1900s","The doctors said I was mad, that my brain didn't work right","Now I believe I have no brain at all, but I see things others cannot—the truth beneath the surface"],"agenda":["Follow OZena because she gives me purpose","Understand the truth of this strange world","Prove I'm more than the madman they say I am"],"gifts":[],"background":"Hirnloser was a psychiatric patient from early 1900s America who was thrown back in time by Dr. Henkle's Compass Rose. The doctors said he was mad, that his brain didn't work right, and over time Hirnloser came to believe he has no brain at all. Despite (or because of) his perceived madness, he sees truths others miss—patterns, connections, and hidden meanings that escape rational minds. He speaks in riddles, rhymes, and fragmented sentences, moving with jerky, unsettling motions. He followed OZena because she gave him purpose when no one else would. He appears at Margareta's village dance and later helps kidnap Klaus to test the Hunters.","notes":"ROLEPLAYING:\n- Speech: Riddles, rhymes, fragmented sentences\n- Mannerisms: Jerky movements, tilts head at odd angles, stares intensely\n- Insight: Despite madness, perceives truths others miss\n\nKEY MOMENT: At the dance, he speaks this riddle: 'The scarecrow sees what you cannot. The tin man feels nothing but knows everything. The lion roars but runs away. And the girl with the silver shoes walks the yellow road to death.'\n\nIf captured, he reveals: 'The wizard in emerald is not what he seems. He steals what he cannot create. The rose blooms red with blood.'\n\nDEVELOPMENT: In Part Three of the campaign, he becomes The Genius when he realizes his mind is his greatest gift.","conditions":[]},"flags":{"scenario":"Ozena Part One - The Yellow Village","inspiration":"The Wizard of Oz - Scarecrow","role":"Mad prophet who sees hidden truths, kidnapper testing the Hunters","timeDisplaced":true,"originalEra":"Early 1900s America"},"_id":"5043d071a8175e06"}
{"name":"Lowe the Brave Fighter - The Transformed Coward","type":"npc","img":"icons/creatures/mammals/cat-hunched-glowing-red.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"biography":"Lowe was once called a coward—a lion-faced man who adapted to whoever seemed to be winning, never standing firm for anything. But through his journey with Dorothea (OZena) and the trials they faced, Lowe has undergone a dramatic transformation. He has found his courage and embraced true heroism. Now Lowe the Brave Fighter stands firm when others flee, speaks with confidence, and meets eyes directly. He no longer adapts to the winning side—he has chosen his loyalty (to Henkle or to the Hunters depending on Dorothea's fate and how the previous scenarios concluded) and defends it without wavering. His transformation represents the completion of a character arc, from cowardly opportunist to genuine hero. When the Hunters encounter him in Smaragd, he will either stand as their enemy (defending Henkle) or as a potential ally (if Dorothea vouched for them or if he's been shown evidence of Henkle's betrayal). His presence is commanding and his newfound courage is infectious to allies around him. If he survives the confrontation and is redeemed, Lowe thanks the Hunters for showing him that courage isn't the absence of fear—it's acting despite it. He may become a Hunter himself or return to his own time to live boldly.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I was called a coward, but I have found my courage","I am a lion-faced warrior who stands firm when others flee","I will protect those I care about, no matter the cost","My loyalty is chosen, not purchased"],"gifts":[{"name":"Hero","description":"Lowe has overcome his cowardice and embraced heroism. **Fearless:** Immune to fear effects and mind control attempts. **Inspiring Presence:** Allied NPCs within 30 feet gain +1 to their Opposition Level when fighting alongside Lowe. **Last Stand:** When reduced to 0 Wounds, Lowe can take one final dramatic action before falling unconscious (attack, speech, or helping an ally)."}],"conditions":[],"agenda":["Defend those I've chosen to protect","Prove that courage can be found, not just born with","Stand firm regardless of who seems to be winning"],"notes":"Lowe's transformation is complete—he no longer exhibits cowardly behavior. If shown evidence of Henkle's betrayal, he turns against the doctor immediately, heartbroken but resolute. He works well with Hirnloser and Dose as a coordinated team. Voice: Strong and confident, no longer hesitant. Mannerisms: Direct eye contact, protective stance. If redeemed, he offers to help the Hunters in future scenarios."},"_id":"755ee23ffcd0ea42"}
{"name":"Margareta Westen - The Good Witch","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/symbols/runes-triangle-yellow.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":7,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Margareta Westen is a wealthy noblewoman who was born with a facial deformity that made her an outcast from high society despite her wealth. Rather than become bitter, she used her magic and fortune to create a haven in the village of Gelb where the rejected, disfigured, and diseased could live in peace and dignity. Margareta is one of four witches who formed a coven to protect the Compass Rose by splitting it into four pieces. She holds the western (yellow) piece. Unlike typical fairy tale witches, Margareta and her sisters are guardians trying to prevent the powerful artifact from falling into the wrong hands. They knew that when united, the Compass Rose could summon storms, throw people between worlds, and tear holes in reality. Margareta is genuinely kind—maternal, warm, and compassionate. She welcomes the Hunters to Gelb and explains her mission to provide safety for outcasts. Nearly fifty people with leontiasis, elephantiasis, severe burns, missing limbs, and other disfiguring conditions live in her village without shame. She uses her magic to ease their pain and her wealth to provide for their needs. Her magic focuses on two branches: Emotion Manipulation (she can alter emotional states, making people calm, afraid, angry, or loving) and Telekinesis (moving objects with her mind, including disarming opponents or creating barriers). Despite her power (OL Hard 7), Margareta has only 1 Wound—her compassion and reluctance to harm even those who threaten her is both her greatest strength and her fatal weakness. When OZena comes to kill her and take the Compass Rose piece, Margareta shows compassion even to her would-be murderer, recognizing Dorothea's desperation and suffering.","descriptors":["I am a wealthy noblewoman born with facial deformity who uses magic and fortune to help outcasts","I guard the western (yellow) piece of the Compass Rose to prevent its misuse","My compassion is genuine but makes me vulnerable—I hesitate to harm even enemies","I can manipulate emotions and move objects with my mind"],"agenda":["Protect my village of Gelb and the outcasts who live here in peace","Guard my piece of the Compass Rose from those who would misuse it","Use my magic to ease suffering wherever I find it","Stop OZena before she kills more witches","Show compassion even to those who seek to harm me"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":3,"max":3},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":0}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Witch - Emotion Manipulation","description":"Margareta can perform a Check to alter the emotional state of anyone she can see within 60 feet. She can make them feel calm (ending rage or panic), afraid (causing them to flee or freeze), angry (turning them hostile to others), or loving (making them trust her or each other). This emotional manipulation lasts for one entire Scene. Victims can resist by making a Check against her Opposition Level (Hard 7). Margareta uses this compassionately—calming frightened villagers, making aggressive visitors peaceful, or helping traumatized people feel love again. But it can also be used tactically in combat.","somaCost":1},{"name":"Witch - Telekinesis","description":"Margareta can move objects with her mind within 60 feet. She can lift and throw items weighing up to 200 pounds. In combat, she can use telekinesis to: disarm opponents by yanking weapons from their hands, create barriers by stacking objects, hurl objects as weapons (treating this as a normal attack Check), pin enemies by dropping heavy items on them, or manipulate the environment to her advantage. Her telekinetic control is precise enough to operate door locks, turn pages, or perform delicate tasks from a distance.","somaCost":1}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Margareta represents the truly good witch—kind, maternal, genuinely helpful. Voice is warm and maternal with slight German accent; touches people gently when speaking; maintains eye contact; smiles despite her facial deformity. Her tragedy: she provides everything the protagonists need (safety, compassion, understanding) but OZena has been manipulated into seeing her as an obstacle. If Margareta survives Part One, she becomes valuable ally: provides information about Compass Rose and other witches; may give Hunters her piece for safekeeping; warns about Helga in Rot and Henkle in Smaragd; can help in final confrontation. If she dies: village of Gelb falls into despair; outcasts may turn hostile blaming Hunters; her death weighs heavily on moral outcome of campaign. Key moment: when confronted by OZena, Margareta shows compassion rather than fighting back, trying to understand Dorothea's suffering. This can be catalyst for OZena's redemption if Hunters intervene. Margareta knows: Johanne was murdered two weeks ago in Schiltach; OZena is being manipulated by Dr. Henkle; Henkle is false wizard in Smaragd; incomplete Compass Rose is incredibly dangerous. Her yellow Compass Rose piece resembles amber needle that hums with energy and points toward Smaragd."},"_id":"78b9c067f3c96cbf"}
{"name":"Dose the Giant in Love - The Transformed Tin Man","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/life/heart-cross-strong-flame-purple-pink.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"biography":"Dose was once hollow metal, a tin man feeling nothing, moving mechanically through existence. But during the events in Smaragd, something miraculous happened: he fell in love with a villager of the Emerald Village, and his heart returned. Dose the Giant in Love is undergoing a physical transformation—wherever his beloved touches him, flesh replaces steel. Patches of exposed skin appear on his arms, chest, and face. He moves more fluidly than before, speaks emotionally rather than mechanically, and constantly talks about his beloved. His transformation represents love's power to restore humanity and vulnerability. When the Hunters encounter him, he's torn between loyalty to Henkle (who brought him here) and his desire to protect his beloved. If his beloved is threatened or if the Hunters appeal to his newfound emotions, he can be convinced to stand down or even help. He's protective and emotional rather than the hollow, mechanical being he once was. If he survives the confrontation, Dose chooses to stay in 1780 with his beloved—the Hunters witness the last of his metal armor falling away, leaving him fully human again. Love literally saved his humanity. His story is the most hopeful of the three companions.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I was hollow metal, feeling nothing","But I have fallen in love and my heart has returned","Where love touches, flesh replaces steel","I am becoming human again"],"gifts":[{"name":"Of Steel and Love","description":"Dose's armor is slowly being replaced by living flesh wherever his beloved touches him. **Partial Immunity:** Most of Dose's body still has metal armor covering it, providing immunity to physical attacks (swords, arrows, etc.) except where flesh is exposed. **Vulnerable Heart:** The area around Dose's heart is now flesh, protected only by the small door in his chest. Attacking this spot requires 1 Penalty on the Check but bypasses all armor if successful. **Love's Strength:** When fighting to protect his beloved (if present or threatened), Dose can act twice in one Exchange, his love granting supernatural determination."}],"conditions":[],"agenda":["Protect my beloved at all costs","Find a way to stay in this time with the one I love","Become fully human again through love's power"],"notes":"Dose's transformation is ongoing and visible—patches of flesh on his arms, chest, face. He speaks constantly about his beloved. If his beloved is present, he's extremely protective. If the Hunters threaten her, he fights to the death. If they protect her or promise to help them stay together, he becomes an ally. He weeps openly when discussing Dorothea's fate. Voice: Emotional, no longer monotone. Mannerisms: Touches the flesh patches, protective gestures. His ending is the happiest—fully human, in love, choosing to stay."},"_id":"7a1ea79c618e3ba5"}
{"name":"Hirnloser the Scarecrow - Original Version","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/perception/eye-ringed-glow-angry-red.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"biography":"Hirnloser is a psychiatric patient from early 1900s America who was institutionalized for mental illness. The doctors said he was mad, that his brain didn't work right. Over time, Hirnloser internalized this diagnosis and came to believe he has no brain at all—that he's empty-headed like a scarecrow. He was displaced through time along with OZena, Lowe, and Dose when Dr. Henkle's incomplete Compass Rose malfunctioned. Despite his apparent madness, Hirnloser sees things others cannot—the truth beneath the surface, patterns in chaos, connections between events. He speaks constantly in riddles, rhymes, and fragmented sentences, his movements jerky and unsettling. At the village dance in Gelb, he approaches the Hunters and speaks cryptically: 'The scarecrow sees what you cannot. The tin man feels nothing but knows everything. The lion roars but runs away. And the girl with the silver shoes walks the yellow road to death.' In the swamp scene, Hirnloser guards Klaus but can be reasoned with if Hunters show understanding. If captured, he reveals important truths in riddles: 'The wizard in emerald is not what he seems. He steals what he cannot create. The rose blooms red with blood.' This is his ORIGINAL form—by Part Three, he transforms into Hirnloser the Genius when he realizes his mind is his greatest gift.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I am a psychiatric patient from the early 1900s","The doctors said my brain didn't work right","I believe I have no brain at all, just straw and emptiness","But I see things others cannot—the truth beneath the surface"],"gifts":[{"name":"Mad Insight","description":"Despite (or because of) his madness, Hirnloser perceives truths others miss. Once per Scene, he can ask the Storyteller one question about the current situation and receive a truthful answer, though it will be delivered in riddles or cryptic language. Additionally, Hirnloser cannot be deceived by illusions or lies—he always sees the truth, even if he can't articulate it clearly."}],"conditions":[],"agenda":["Follow OZena because she gives me purpose","Understand the truth of this strange world","Prove I'm more than the madman they say I am","Protect my companions in my own strange way"],"notes":"This is Hirnloser's ORIGINAL FORM in Part One (before transformation to Genius in Part Three). Speaks in riddles/rhymes/fragments. Jerky movements, tilts head oddly, intense stares. Appears at village dance, guards Klaus in swamp. If captured, reveals important clues about Henkle in riddles. Can be reasoned with if shown understanding. Character arc: Madman who thinks he has no brain → Genius who realizes his mind is his weapon. Voice: Fragmented, singsong, cryptic. Mannerisms: Jerky movements, odd angles, dancing steps."},"_id":"7c394f72327182b6"}
{"name":"The Hammerheads - Elite Guards","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/head/helm-barbute-banded-steel.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":false,"biography":"The Hammerheads are Helga's elite guards, warriors who wear massive hammer-shaped helmets that extend down to completely cover their heads and chests. These specially designed helmets provide incredible protection for the upper body but leave the lower body vulnerable. The Hammerheads are blood-bound servants like the Porcelain Dolls, mind-controlled by Helga's magic and forced to serve as her personal bodyguards. They work in pairs with coordinated tactics: one engages directly while the other flanks, using their heavy helmets as weapons by headbutting opponents. They protect Helga fanatically, willing to die for her without hesitation. The only way to damage a Hammerhead is to specifically target their lower body (legs, abdomen), which requires accepting 1 Penalty on the attack Check, or to use magic and area attacks that don't require precise targeting. If the Infusion of Purity breaks Helga's blood magic control over them, they immediately stop fighting and flee in confusion. Beneath the helmets are ordinary soldiers from nearby towns, kidnapped and enslaved by Helga's cult. Some have been serving for years, completely losing their original identities. The helmets are works of craftsmanship—heavy iron shaped like massive hammers, with eye slits and breathing holes, weighing over 40 pounds. Only the strongest warriors can wear them in combat.","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":1,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["We are Helga's elite guards","Warriors who wear massive hammer-shaped helmets","Our helmets protect our heads and torsos completely","We serve the Red Witch without question"],"gifts":[{"name":"Hammerhead Helmet","description":"The Hammerheads wear specially designed helmets that extend down to cover their heads and chests completely. **Head/Chest Immunity:** Attacks targeting the head or chest automatically miss or deal no damage. **Vulnerable Lower Body:** Attackers can target the lower body (legs, abdomen), but this requires 1 Penalty on the attack Check. Magic or area attacks that don't require precise targeting bypass this protection. The helmet can also be used as a battering weapon for headbutt attacks."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"Hammerheads typically work in pairs: one engages directly while the other flanks. They use coordinated tactics and their helmets to headbutt opponents. They protect Helga fanatically in her mansion. If the Infusion breaks Helga's control, they stop fighting and flee. There are usually 4-6 Hammerheads guarding Helga's ritual chamber. Smart players will target their legs or use magic to bypass the helmet protection. The helmets make them slow but nearly invulnerable from the waist up."},"_id":"a362e48c0e3fb6cc"}
{"name":"Dr. Norman Henkle - The False Wizard","type":"npc","img":"icons/magic/air/air-burst-spiral-blue-gray.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"background":"Dr. Norman Henkle was a researcher in early 1900s America studying mental illness. He discovered the Compass Rose in his asylum's archives, recognized its power, and experimented on patients (Lowe, Hirnloser, Dose, Dorothea). The Rose malfunctioned, throwing them backward in time to 1780 Germany. Trapped and terrified, Henkle hid his ignorance behind knowledge from the future—mentioning penicillin, steam engines, germ theory made him seem like a wizard. He murdered or drove out Griselda (the fourth witch), fortified Smaragd as his castle, and manipulated OZena into killing the other witches so he could collect all Compass Rose pieces and return home (or conquer this era). He planned OZena's death after she delivered Helga's piece. He is a false wizard: charismatic manipulator with future knowledge but no real magic, vulnerable when confronted by actual experts. His Hot-Air Balloon is his escape plan—powered by Time Tokens harvested from temporal anomalies caused by the Rose's presence. He's the true villain: not broken by suffering like OZena, but a calculating sociopath who caused all of this.","descriptors":["I am false wizard from the future (1900s) trapped in 1780, using future knowledge to fake magic","I orchestrated everything: experimenting on patients, causing time displacement, manipulating OZena","My Hot-Air Balloon powered by Time Tokens is my escape plan back to my era or to rule this one","I murdered/drove out Griselda and fortified Smaragd, now collecting Compass Rose pieces","I am master manipulator with Silver Tongue but plagiarist—vulnerable when facing true experts"],"agenda":["Collect all four Compass Rose pieces to control time portal","Use OZena to murder witches then eliminate her after she delivers Helga's piece","Harvest Time Tokens from temporal anomalies to power my Hot-Air Balloon","Return to my own era as a powerful time traveler, or conquer 1780 with future knowledge","Prevent anyone from discovering I'm not a real wizard","Kill the Hunters before they expose my deception or stop my plans"],"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":2,"extra":{"value":0,"max":0}}},"gifts":[{"name":"Hot-Air Balloon (Time Tokens)","description":"Henkle's escape plan is a Hot-Air Balloon powered by temporal anomalies. He harvests **Time Tokens** which function as countdown: he places 1 Token when combat starts, 1 Token when significantly delayed, 1 Token when Hunters lost in Illusory Labyrinth. When he accumulates **3 Time Tokens**, his balloon is ready to launch. At 3 Tokens, he attempts escape: takes 1 Exchange to board, 1 more Exchange to launch, must succeed Navigation Check or balloon drifts (Hunters make Athletics Check to catch ropes). Once airborne, extremely difficult to stop. Balloon can be sabotaged: destroying control mechanism (OL 5 Check), cutting tether ropes (Athletics Check), puncturing envelope (ranged attack).","somaCost":0},{"name":"Silver Tongue","description":"Henkle is master manipulator. When engaging in social manipulation, persuasion, deception, or intimidation based on his false wizard persona, increase his Opposition Level by +2 to **OL 7 (Hard)**. This applies to: convincing NPCs he's a wizard, persuading villagers to obey, manipulating OZena, deceiving Hunters about his intentions. NPCs are especially vulnerable—they almost always believe him unless given overwhelming evidence he's lying.","somaCost":0},{"name":"Plagiarist (Weakness)","description":"Henkle's power is entirely borrowed—future knowledge pretending to be magic. If confronted by a **true expert** in a field he's faking (real wizard, genuine scholar, actual doctor from his era), his Opposition Level **drops to OL 3 (Easy)** for that Scene. He becomes flustered, makes mistakes, contradicts himself. Examples: real magic user recognizes he has no magical aura, historian catches anachronisms, doctor realizes his medical knowledge stops at 1900s. This is his critical vulnerability.","somaCost":0}],"conditions":[],"specialNotes":"Henkle is the true villain—not tragic like OZena but calculating sociopath. Voice: smooth American accent, anachronistic slang. Manner: constantly smiling, checks escape routes, fake wizard gestures (meaningless hand-waving). Combat: avoids direct confrontation, uses minions (Villagers of Emerald, Canine Tigers), focuses on harvesting Time Tokens while others fight. If exposed as fraud: panics, makes desperate mistakes, tries to escape immediately. If balloon destroyed: loses composure entirely, may offer desperate bargains. **Redemption**: NONE. Unlike OZena, he's irredeemable—caused suffering deliberately for power. **Ultimate Confrontation**: Hunters can: destroy balloon forcing him to face justice, expose him to Villagers causing revolt, trap him in 1780 forever, or let him escape (bittersweet—villain escapes but crisis ends). **If OZena Redeemed**: she becomes his nemesis, removes Silver Slippers to stop him, accepts being trapped in 1780 to ensure he can't escape. **Compass Rose Finale**: If Henkle activates complete Rose, creates massive time portal—Hunters must decide: stop him, send companions home, or prevent temporal catastrophe."},"_id":"a3e562ff52f48fe1"}
{"name":"Porcelain Princess - The Disfigured Noblewoman","type":"npc","img":"icons/equipment/head/mask-carved-white-blue.webp","system":{"npcType":"adversary","oppositionLevel":5,"isMainNPC":true,"biography":"The Porcelain Princess appears as a beautiful woman wearing an elaborate porcelain mask and elegant gown, but beneath the mask, her face is hideously disfigured by disease. She was once a noblewoman who society rejected after illness destroyed her beauty. In desperation, she sought out Helga and accepted the witch's offer: power and purpose in exchange for eternal service. Now she manages Helga's cult in the village of Rot, organizing blood rituals and maintaining order among the mind-controlled villagers. She is surrounded by her Porcelain Dolls—twelve masked servants carrying various weapons who stand perfectly still until commanded. The Princess knows why the Hunters have come and offers them three choices: leave now and Helga will spare OZena (a lie), join the cult and receive Helga's blessing (eternal servitude), or try to rescue OZena and die in the attempt. If the Hunters refuse her deal, she signals her Dolls to attack. If defeated and spared, she may remove her mask voluntarily, revealing her disfigurement and explaining how Helga's promises of beauty were lies. She possesses a key to Helga's mansion and a vial of glowing blood, gasping when defeated: 'You fools... you've doomed her. Helga will drink OZena's blood before you reach her!'","attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I was a noblewoman disfigured by disease","Society rejected me, so I embraced Helga's offer","Power in exchange for service","I manage her cult and keep the villagers in line"],"gifts":[{"name":"Cult Leader","description":"The Porcelain Princess commands the Porcelain Dolls with perfect coordination. As long as she lives and can see them, the Dolls act with +1 OL when following her direct commands. She can command all twelve Dolls to move as a single coordinated unit, creating tactical advantages in combat. If she's killed or incapacitated, the Dolls become disoriented and act independently at their base OL."}],"conditions":[],"notes":"The Porcelain Princess holds the key to Helga's mansion and knows the ritual schedule. If the Infusion of Purity is used on her, she's freed from blood magic control and may become an ally, revealing the truth about Helga's corruption. She carries a vial of blood that glows—this is OZena's blood, being prepared for the ritual. The Princess genuinely believed Helga would restore her beauty but has been betrayed like all of Helga's servants."},"_id":"a79640c8ea2ae09d"}
{"name":"OZena (Dorothea Gray)","type":"npc","img":"icons/svg/mystery-man.svg","system":{"npcType":"adversary","isMainNPC":true,"oppositionLevel":5,"attributes":{"soma":{"current":0,"max":0},"wounds":{"current":0,"max":3,"extra":{"value":0,"max":1}}},"descriptors":["I suffer from ozena, a disease that destroyed my nose and my life","I was thrown back in time, and the only way home is to gather the pieces of the Compass Rose","I will do whatever it takes to end my suffering—even murder"],"agenda":["Collect all four pieces of the Compass Rose","Get home to my own time","Find a cure for my disease"],"gifts":[{"name":"The Silver Slippers - Short-Range Teleport","description":"Once per Exchange, OZena can teleport up to 30 feet to any location she can see. This doesn't count as an action and can be used to avoid attacks or reposition instantly."},{"name":"The Silver Slippers - Long-Distance Teleport","description":"Once per Scene, OZena can teleport to any location within 1 mile that she has previously visited. This requires her full action. The Silver Slippers are permanently attached to her feet and cannot be removed without killing her."}],"background":"Dorothea Gray grew up in early 1900s America with dreams of becoming a doctor. Her life was destroyed when she contracted ozena—a terrible disease that slowly destroyed her nasal cavity, leaving her face disfigured. Desperate for a cure, she sought out Dr. Norman Henkle, who possessed a partially completed artifact called the Compass Rose. The incomplete artifact malfunctioned, throwing Dorothea and three other patients backward in time to 1780 Germany. Dr. Henkle convinced the desperate Dorothea that four witches held the pieces of the Compass Rose and were evil, and that killing them was necessary to return home. Dorothea became OZena—a killer who has already murdered Johanne in Schiltach. Her face is horribly disfigured, with her nose completely gone. She covers the lower half of her face with a silver mask. She wears enchanted Silver Slippers that allow her to teleport.","notes":"ROLEPLAYING:\n- Voice: Muffled by her mask, tinged with pain and desperation\n- Mannerisms: Keeps one hand on her mask, moves with purpose, eyes constantly scanning\n- Motivation: She was a good person broken by suffering and manipulation\n- Tragedy: Every witch she kills makes her more monstrous, but she's too desperate to stop\n- Redemption: She can be saved if the Hunters show her the truth about Henkle\n\nWHAT SHE KNOWS:\n- Dr. Henkle can send people through time using the Compass Rose\n- The Compass Rose needs all four pieces to function safely\n- She's already killed Johanne and taken the North (Black) piece\n- Henkle told her the witches are evil and must be eliminated\n\nWHAT SHE DOESN'T KNOW:\n- Henkle is lying about the witches being evil\n- The incomplete Compass Rose is more dangerous than helpful\n- Henkle plans to abandon her once he has what he needs\n- Her actions are part of a larger scheme by the One Who Plots in the Shadows","conditions":[]},"flags":{"scenario":"Ozena Part One - The Yellow Village","inspiration":"The Wizard of Oz - Dorothy","role":"Tragic antagonist hunting witches, can be redeemed","timeDisplaced":true,"originalEra":"Early 1900s America"},"_id":"c5fcbc12a4625181"}
